1. What are Java 8 Streams?

In Java 8, Streams are a powerful feature introduced to process collections of data in a functional style. They allow you to perform operations like filtering, mapping, and reducing data in a clean, declarative way instead of writing long loops.

A Stream does not store data. It processes data from a source such as:
Collections (List, Set)
Arrays
Files
I/O channels

Advantages:
Less code
More readable
Functional programming style
Supports parallel processing


Think of a stream as a pipeline of operations applied to data.

A Stream pipeline has 3 parts:

Source → Intermediate Operations → Terminal Operation

Intermediate = returns Stream
Terminal = returns result/value

Intermediate operations return another Stream and are lazy (they do not execute until a terminal operation is called).

| Operation       | Description                                |
| --------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| `filter()`      | Filters elements based on condition        |
| `map()`         | Transforms elements                        |
| `flatMap()`     | Flattens nested streams                    |
| `distinct()`    | Removes duplicate elements                 |
| `sorted()`      | Sorts elements                             |
| `limit()`       | Limits number of elements                  |
| `skip()`        | Skips first N elements                     |
| `peek()`        | Performs action while processing           |
| `mapToInt()`    | Converts stream to IntStream               |
| `mapToLong()`   | Converts stream to LongStream              |
| `mapToDouble()` | Converts stream to DoubleStream            |
| `boxed()`       | Converts primitive stream to object stream |


Terminal operations end the stream pipeline and produce a result or side effect.

| Operation          | Description                      |
| ------------------ | -------------------------------- |
| `forEach()`        | Performs action for each element |
| `forEachOrdered()` | Ordered version of forEach       |
| `collect()`        | Converts stream to collection    |
| `reduce()`         | Reduces stream to single value   |
| `count()`          | Counts elements                  |
| `min()`            | Finds minimum element            |
| `max()`            | Finds maximum element            |
| `findFirst()`      | Returns first element            |
| `findAny()`        | Returns any element              |
| `anyMatch()`       | Checks if any element matches    |
| `allMatch()`       | Checks if all elements match     |
| `noneMatch()`      | Checks if no element matches     |
| `toArray()`        | Converts stream to array         |
| `iterator()`       | Returns iterator                 |






















